<p>
  Let <m>f</m> be a differentiable function of <m>x</m> (whose formula is not known)
  and recall that <m>\frac{d}{dx}[f(x)]</m> and <m>f'(x)</m> are interchangeable notations.
  We want to find derivatives of various expressions that involve <m>f(x)</m>.
</p>
<p> 
  For example, if we are interested in finding the derivative of <m>f(x)^3+cx</m>, we can use the chain rule and the sum rule to find that 
  <me>
    \dfrac{d}{dx}\left[f(x)^3+5x\right]=3(f(x))^2f'(x)+5.
  </me>
</p>

<p>
  Determine each of the following derivatives of combinations of explicit functions of 
  <m>x</m>, the unknown function <m>f</m>, and an arbitrary constant <m>c</m>.
    <ol marker="a." cols="2">
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{d}{dx} \left[ x^2 + f(x) \right]=</m> <mathInput name="mi1"/>
          <answer name= "PA_2-7-1_ans1" matchPartial><award> <when> $mi1 = 2x+f'(x) or $mi1=2x+d/dx(f(x)) or $mi1=2x+df/dx</when></award> </answer>
        </p>
        
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{d}{dx} \left[ x^2 f(x) \right]=</m><mathInput name="mi2"/>
          <answer name= "PA_2-7-1_ans2" matchPartial><award> <when> $mi2 = 2x*f(x)+x^2*f'(x) or $mi2=2x*f(x)+x^2*d/dx(f(x)) or $mi2=2x*f(x)+x^2*df/dx</when></award> </answer>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{d}{dx} \left[ c + x + f(x)^2 \right]=</m><mathInput name="mi3"/>
          <answer name= "PA_2-7-1_ans3"><award> <when> $mi3 = 1+2f(x)*f'(x)<!-- or $mi2=1+2f(x)*d/dx(f(x)) or $mi2=1+2f(x)*df/dx--> </when></award> </answer>
        
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{d}{dx} \left[ f(x^2) \right]=</m><mathInput name="mi4"/>
          <answer name= "PA_2-7-1_ans4" matchPartial><award> <when> $mi4 = f'(x^2)*2x </when></award> </answer>

        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{d}{dx} \left[ xf(x) + f(cx) + cf(x) \right]</m>
       <mathInput name="mi5"/>
        </p>
          <answer name= "PA_2-7-1_ans5" matchPartial><award> <when> $mi5 = f(x)+x*f'(x)+c*f'(cx)+c*f'(x) </when></award> </answer>
      </li>
    </ol>
</p>
